HHS Exploration

Data description

This is data from the 2018 Southeastern PA Household Health Survey (SEPA-HHS). More details are available in Week 9’s module under HHS Data and Materials

Cleaning

The following script imports and cleans the data housed in an SPSS .sav file. To re-construct the data, set your working directory to the one housing the SPSS file and run the script

library(foreign)

HHS <- read.spss("HHS18AR_2.sav", use.value.labels = TRUE, to.data.frame = TRUE, max.value.labels = 98, add.undeclared.levels = "no")


keep <- c("COUNTY","ZIPCODE","ZIPREGION","SEX01","RESPAGE_4CAT","TOTKIDS","NUMADULT2",
          "HLTHA5","DOCVST3","HOSPERA2","INSUREDA2","BMI","XERCISE_2CAT","FRUITS")

HHS_clean <- HHS[, keep]

HHS_clean <- na.omit(HHS_clean)

for (i in 1:nrow(HHS_clean)){
  if (HHS_clean$COUNTY[i] == "Philadelphia"){
    HHS_clean$COUNTY_2CAT[i] <- "Philadelphia"
  } else {
    HHS_clean$COUNTY_2CAT[i] <- "Not Philadelphia"
  }
}

I decided to use only these variables based just on heuristics. If you would like to include more, you are free to do so by simply adding the column names to the keep object. Be aware, that depending on the variable, there may be so many NA values that the na.omit command will exclude nearly everyone.

Here we end up with 2938 observations.

The outcome: BMI

BMI was chosen as the outcome because it is numeric and somewhat normally distributed. However, following week 9, you may use multilevel logistic regression with binary outcomes.

Note that the BMI distribution is a bit skewed overall:

require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(BMI)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Histogram of BMI values")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can use the logarithm if we think that will help

HHS_clean$logBMI <- log(HHS_clean$BMI)


ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(logBMI)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Histogram of log(BMI) values")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

One of the issues we might have with \(\log(BMI)\) is that our variance components will be very small later. Here’s what we can do:

  1. Build a model using the un-transformed (raw) BMI values as the outcome and check the diagnostic plots (especially at level 1)

  2. Compare these plots to one with the log-transformed data

If the assumptions are violated much more by #1, go with #2, knowing that interpretation is a bit hampered, and that variance components will be quite small

Incidentally, the ICCs are nearly identical, and quite small. This suggests that variation in BMI is mostly at the individual level. So we might not be gaining much by modeling ZIPREGION as random, but we can still profit from the ability to test the effect of living in Philadelphia on BMI using the clustering.

Below is a function that computes ICCs from unconstrained lmer models.

# function to compute ICCs from unconstrained lmer models
ICClmer <- function(formula = NULL, data = NULL, model = NULL){
  if (is.null(formula)){
    x <- data.frame(VarCorr(model))
    x$vcov[1]/(x$vcov[1]+x$vcov[2])
  } else{
    model <- lmer(formula, data)
    x <- data.frame(VarCorr(model))
    x$vcov[1]/(x$vcov[1]+x$vcov[2])
  }
}

ICClmer(model = rawmod)
## [1] 0.02682736
ICClmer(model = logmod)
## [1] 0.02741321

Many of the predictors are categorical, so we can use boxplots to visualize relationships.

For example, let’s look at the distribution of BMI with and without insurance. We’ll use the un-transformed BMI

ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(x = INSUREDA2, y = BMI)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = T)

How about Age?

ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(x = RESPAGE_4CAT, y = BMI)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = T)

Or reported Health?

ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(x = HLTHA5, y = BMI)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = T)

How about with \(\log(BMI)\)

ggplot(HHS_clean, aes(x = HLTHA5, y = logBMI)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = T)

Going forward

For your assignment:

  1. Pick a few variables you believe might explain BMI at level-1.
  2. Try to find a good fitting level 1 model
  • Note, that random slopes might lead to singular fits. So it’s ok if your models only have random intercepts
  1. Add in the Two-County Predictor at level-2
  2. Write up the results and interpretations
